node.text:
Photo by @itsrachelhannah #AdobeRisingStars⁠⁠
• ⁠⁠
Hey everyone! It’s my final day of the takeover! I hope you’ve enjoyed my photos and also sharing some behind the scenes of how I edited them using Lightroom mobile. I know I have thoroughly enjoyed sharing them with you.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
So my last post is a winter scene from my time spent at my local deer park. The herd of deer here are called fallow deer which were introduced to the UK in the 11th century by the Normans. Due to their longevity here in the UK, they’re now considered native. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
The reason I visited the park in the winter is because it’s a lot quieter and the chances of finding the deer are higher. Don’t get me wrong, I love the challenge of finding them but when it’s bitterly cold and snowing, you appreciate that higher chance!⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Once I found the herd I quietly found a spot and waited for the stag to sit down once I had the composition in mind. It took longer than expected, but after a quick shot with the 100-400mm lens, I was happy with what I captured and took it back to edit! Check out my final story on how I used the healing tool to get my ideal shot. (P.S. I added in the snow effect using a preset after)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Adobe Photoshop Lightroom on August 19, 2021 tagging @itsrachelhannah. May be an image of animal, nature and grass.

node.text:
Photo by @itsrachelhannah #AdobeRisingStars⁠
• ⁠
Hey everyone, for day four of my takeover I would like to share with you a special breed of cow, the Highland cow! Often known as the gentle giants of Scotland, their beautiful red locks and distinctive long horns make them easily recognisable. It was such a pleasure to be able to sit amongst the blooming heather and photograph them. ⁠
⁠
Photographing animals and wildlife is a great way to practice patience as it requires a great amount to be able to capture the photo you have in mind! The buzz you get inside is definitely worth the wait!⁠
⁠
Next time you’re out in nature, make it a challenge to capture wildlife and you’ll see what I mean! ☺

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Adobe Photoshop Lightroom on August 18, 2021 tagging @itsrachelhannah. May be an image of nature and road.

node.text:
Photo by @itsrachelhannah #AdobeRisingStars⁠⁠
• ⁠⁠
Today’s photo is of one of the best roads in the Peak District (in my opinion). This road cuts through Mam Tor which is a 517 m hill in the High Peak of Derbyshire, England. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
The name Mam Tor actually means “mother hill", because frequent landslips on the hills eastern face have resulted in a number of "mini-hills" beneath it which I tried to bring to life in my edit. See today’s story on how I did that!⁠⁠
⁠⁠
I took this photo on a post-Christmas wander around the hills before it got busy. The sun had just started to clear the mist within the surrounding valleys as it rose over the hills and there was a real sense of calm. After the madness of Christmas and weeks leading up to it, getting out amongst nature was a welcomed distraction. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
It’s well-known that getting outdoors in nature can be good for people’s health and well-being, but how long is enough to feel the benefits?⁠⁠
⁠⁠
How often do you spend outside amongst nature?

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Adobe Photoshop Lightroom on August 17, 2021 tagging @itsrachelhannah. May be an image of nature.

node.text:
Photo by @itsrachelhannah #AdobeRisingStars⁠
• ⁠
I’ve been lucky enough to visit this beautiful part of Scotland twice now and both times were super special. Glenfinnan Viaduct had been on my list to visit for years, so finally getting to experience the magic of this special place is a memory I won’t forget.⁠
⁠
The main reason to visit is to see the famous Jacobite Steam train, also known as the ‘Hogwarts Express’, pass along viaduct. If you didn’t know, the filming of the second and third Harry Potter films took place in this area with the Hogwarts Express calling at Glenfinnan station!⁠
⁠
Have you ever been to the Scottish highlands?

Photo by @itsrachelhannah #AdobeRisingStars⁠
• ⁠
Hey everyone! I’m looking forward to sharing some of my work with you this week. ⁠
⁠
A lot of my work is based outdoors, whether that’s exploring the majestic highlands of Scotland or simply experiencing the wonders of nature in my own back garden.⁠
⁠
This particular photo is of a juvenile Robin that graced me with its presence whilst I was relaxing in my garden during Covid lockdown. Bobbing its head up and down it was almost like it was telling me it wanted its photo taken. So, I grabbed my camera and waited until the Robin perched on the nearby log. As luck would have it, the sun pierced through the trees at the exact moment and captured this beauty in all its glory. I like to call this photo “The fresh feathers of new life”.⁠
⁠
Visit @lightroom’s Instagram story to see how I edited this shot to really make the Robin pop!

Photo by @aman_rebel for #AdobeRisingStars ⁠⁠
• ⁠⁠
This photo was taken at Mount “Entoto” (እንጦጦ: Amharic). It is the highest peak overlooking the city of Addis Ababa, and has nice views of the city. The mountain is densely covered by eucalyptus trees that were imported from Australia during the reign of Menelik II, and mostly planted during Emperor Haile Selassie’s reign. The peak is the highest on this mountain and overlooks the capital city, reaching 3,200 meters above sea level. It is the perfect escape from the city for a pleasant morning excursion. Most locals visit to escape the hustle and bustle of the city and to enjoy the fresh air.⁠⁠
 •⁠⁠
When I look at this photo, I feel peace. The road and trees were all covered with fog that morning. Everything felt magical and peaceful at the same time.

I have been enjoying shooting silhouettes ever since I discovered my passion for street photography.⁠
⁠
I was out for my usual photo walk, hunting for shadows on a random street in my city; not far from where I was waiting for a subject to pass by my frame I saw this classic Volkswagen Beetle. It is very common to see classic VW Beetles on the streets of Addis Ababa, but the beauty of this car's color caught my eye, and shadow of the driver inside created the silhouette I was looking for.

This place is called “Werka,” located in the (Sidamo) South West of Ethiopia. Fun fact: it is believed that coffee has its origins in this region.⁠
• ⁠
As the sun says goodbye to the day and the dark starts to take over the night, people typically collect firewood for their homes for cooking on their way home from work. While passing by the village I saw these four people, including the kid in the middle, with firewood on their shoulders and I immediately got out of the car to capture this magical moment.⁠

Hey everyone! This is Amanuel Tsegaye. I’m a street photographer based in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia. I’m so thrilled to have been given the opportunity to share some of my work this week as part of the 2021 Adobe Rising Stars.⁠⁠
•⁠⁠
I typically find it hard to caption my photos; I believe that photos tell a story by themselves and I capture them to tell the story for me. When I go out for a shoot, I always enjoy the boundless energy of my surroundings. This foggy morning taught me that people wake up early to work for a life they desperately want to live, even in tough times. ⁠⁠

This picture is dedicated to my friend Wesley, who is like a brother to me, he lived and went to Chico State University up in #NorthernCalifornia for six years. This last Spring, there were a lot of things happening at once so we took a trip to San Francisco to get away. We spent hours clearing our minds and deciding on what’s next. We often wondered if life would ever change, would we be successful someday? Is school even worth it? Wesley moved back home to Ventura, CA. I’m very proud of him for receiving his real estate license in Ventura County. After all of his hard work and dedication he figured out what he wanted to do and found his path.
